snippet.textDisplay:
Student: "Sir, can I ask a question?"

Teacher: "Yes!"

Student: "How do you put an elephant inside a fridge?"

Teacher: "I don't know."

Student: "It's easy, you just open the fridge and put it in. I have another question!"

Teacher: "Ok, ask."

Student: "How to put a donkey inside the fridge?"

Teacher: "It's easy, you just open the fridge and put it in."

Student: "No sir, You just open the fridge take out the elephant and put it in." Teacher: "Ooh...ok!!"

Student: "Let me ask another one. If all the animals went to the lion's birthday party, and one animal went missing which one would it be?"

Teacher: "The lion of course! Because it wud eat all the animals."

Student: "No sir, it is the donkey becoz it's still inside the fridge."

Teacher: "Are you kidding me?"

Student: "No sir, 1 last question."

Teacher: "Ok!"

Student: "If there's a river full of crocodiles and you wanted to cross, how would you?"

Teacher: "There's no way, I would need a boat to cross."

Student: "No sir, you just swim and cross it because all the animals went to the lion's birthday party..."

Teacher: "I have my own question, if all the students come to school except one person, who is the person..."

Student: "No idea sir..."

Teacher: "It's you because you are on two weeks suspension."

snippet.textDisplay: I feel Youtube is way over their head in terms of content policing for ad revenue and laws... They're basically the man in the middle for everything. On one hand, I do sympathize. It's not a simple task dealing with a multinational corporation that isn't producing it's own content. On the other, I can't say it's fair to the creators, which are literally their cash cows. Some get preferential treatment, others don't. Depends on how much backlash you can generate through your crowd. I doubt YT is going to implode over what they're doing... But it's sadly just another case of corporate standards and capitalism. It's no longer a freelance platform, you must abide by their, and every other nations rules. Even if they don't make sense, even if you're unaware. Sadly it's down to the individual creator to know the laws of various countries. Youtube has just stepped back from assistance in the past few years. They simply are not provided the man (or woman) power to manually review the increasingly massive amount of content. To an extent, I can say that's to be expected. But everything these days is an algorithm. Manual reviews of videos seem hasty, as if they have a ridiculous queue of videos they are expected to get through. It reminds me a lot of a few other companies I've worked with... Most of which are still very much in business to this day... At the end of the day, whether you pay with time spent watching, or out of your wallet, you're putting money in YT/Google's pocket. They seem to be quite content with that. I'm not saying don't watch youtube videos, as they're essentially the Comcast/Time Warner of video consumption... But if there's other platforms your creators are on, support them by watching their content on that instead. No amount of likes or dislikes, especially on a single yearly video, will truly affect YT's wallet. Lack of viewers will. Bad publicity is still publicity, and will generate views.

snippet.textDisplay: YouTube can never fix YouTube rewind, because YouTube is dead. The original YouTuber creators that made YouTube a great platform to watch videos on, are starting to leave or have left already. The passion and creativity has been drained by money and greed. YouTube is no longer a hobby, but a business. All that's left is money and clout chasers that act as corporate shills and disguise themselves as vloggers, bloggers, make-up channels, etc. Do you honestly look forward to rewinding people like David Dobrik, James Charles and other disingenuous people? In the end, what is there to rewind...? If you read all of this, go do me a favour and watch Nigahiga, one of the last original YouTubers that gives actual meaning to the word.

snippet.textDisplay:
Matt open your eyes! As much as YouTube wants you to believe they’re just a machine they aren’t. They want the facade of platform while at the same time tweaking their algorithm to boost content they approve of and only enforcing rules on what they disapprove of. a la publisher. That’s why there’s so many shadow bans, censorship, idea bias, virtue signaling, deplatforming, and vague rules.

Youtube has an idea of what content is and isn’t acceptable and will do anything behind the curtain to influence you in their direction.
